WEBVTT

00:47.214 --> 00:51.175
"I lay on my pillow
at the Sherry-Netherland Hotel.

00:51.260 --> 00:54.303
"Delicious and destroyed.

00:54.388 --> 00:58.057
"Inhaling the fragrance of the sheets.

00:58.142 --> 01:02.311
"Feeling the warmth of where
you were just laying.

01:02.396 --> 01:05.022
"You make me new with laughter.

01:05.107 --> 01:07.525
"You make me old with wisdom.

01:08.986 --> 01:11.070
You make wine taste sweeter."

01:12.573 --> 01:13.948
Who wrote that?

01:15.451 --> 01:18.995
I write a lot of poetry when I'm inspired.

01:24.251 --> 01:27.837
I guess I shouldn't be surprised
by anything you do.

01:27.921 --> 01:29.380
You shouldn't.

01:30.883 --> 01:32.300
It's insulting.

01:35.512 --> 01:39.182
I have to keep you in line,
or I'll lose you.

01:39.266 --> 01:40.850
Yes, you will.

01:43.187 --> 01:45.480
I don't like the idea of making you older.

01:47.983 --> 01:50.109
I just meant...

01:52.988 --> 01:54.447
I don't know.

02:01.455 --> 02:04.999
It doesn't matter how old l am.

02:05.125 --> 02:07.168
Our souls are the same age.

02:22.976 --> 02:24.352
Oh, God.

02:27.022 --> 02:28.773
You're getting to me.

02:35.322 --> 02:38.658
How do I know I'm not just
going to eat another mushroom

02:38.742 --> 02:42.995
and this room will disappear
and I'll be back on a train to Trenton?

02:43.080 --> 02:45.957
Because l love you, Jane.

02:50.379 --> 02:53.506
This is hard for you. I know it.

02:56.510 --> 02:57.969
You don't want me to talk about it,

02:58.053 --> 03:03.432
but Margaret and Mona have been
your life for the last 40 years.

03:03.517 --> 03:05.393
30.

03:07.396 --> 03:10.982
Listen, I'm not being impulsive,

03:11.066 --> 03:14.026
because I've been thinking
about this all the time.

03:16.113 --> 03:18.406
I want you to be my wife.

03:19.449 --> 03:20.449
What?

03:22.244 --> 03:23.369
Marry me.

03:25.247 --> 03:26.831
Roger, are you serious?

03:26.915 --> 03:28.708
Will you do that for me?

03:43.640 --> 03:46.767
90% of Right Guard users
say they play sports.

03:46.852 --> 03:48.978
60% wear it for their girls as well.

03:49.062 --> 03:53.149
Most impressive, 80% of the fellas
saying "yes" to the question:

03:53.233 --> 03:55.985
"Does Right Guard make you
feel more confident at work?"

03:56.069 --> 03:58.321
Did anyone watch Loretta Young last night?

03:58.405 --> 03:59.864
I was supposed to. What happened?

03:59.948 --> 04:02.617
I can't even describe it, it was so awful.

04:02.701 --> 04:07.163
Creative, think old Donnie Draper will mind
if we think better on a full stomach?

04:08.874 --> 04:10.791
Well, if you'lI all swear
Gillette dropped in.

04:10.876 --> 04:12.585
Are you kidding?

04:12.669 --> 04:14.295
Absolutely.

04:14.379 --> 04:16.422
I'll pretend they're here if you give me
some actual ideas.

04:16.506 --> 04:18.841
Right Guard already has
a great campaign--

04:18.926 --> 04:20.134
men being men.

04:20.260 --> 04:21.969
You know, women smell bad, too.

04:22.054 --> 04:23.262
Not you, of course.

04:23.347 --> 04:24.639
Women haνe perfume.

04:24.723 --> 04:27.099
"Perfume does not fight wetness."

04:27.184 --> 04:29.977
Loretta Young.
She's my dad's favorite.

04:30.062 --> 04:31.270
The aprons.

04:31.355 --> 04:33.814
The nauseating upholstery on the couch.

04:33.899 --> 04:35.733
Strangers who drop by.

04:35.817 --> 04:36.859
Hear from Kinsey?

04:36.944 --> 04:38.319
What do you mean?

04:38.403 --> 04:39.946
Did you read what's going on down there?

04:40.030 --> 04:41.614
In this day and age.

04:41.698 --> 04:43.908
The papers said it's gonna be
Little Rock all over again.

04:43.992 --> 04:46.535
I don't know why people
keep stirring up trouble.

04:46.620 --> 04:47.870
It's bad for business.

04:47.955 --> 04:49.205
Just another reason not to watch TV.

04:49.289 --> 04:50.748
Kurt doesn't even have one.

04:50.832 --> 04:52.500
You have to have one. It's your job.

04:52.584 --> 04:53.793
You're gonna miss the playoff.

04:55.379 --> 04:56.796
It's a different life for single men.

04:56.880 --> 04:59.048
What do you do with your spare time?

04:59.132 --> 05:01.300
I like concerts. I like park.

05:01.385 --> 05:03.219
He saw Bob Dylan at Carnegie Hall.

05:03.303 --> 05:05.096
I heard him on the radio.

05:05.180 --> 05:07.473
So we're not gonna work at all.

05:09.017 --> 05:11.894
Tell Right Guard,
short of a new product just for women,

05:11.979 --> 05:13.270
we need more research and time.

05:13.355 --> 05:14.438
And lunch.

05:16.608 --> 05:18.609
Can we split a lobster?

05:25.742 --> 05:27.785
Does he sound like the album?

05:27.869 --> 05:30.788
When you hear him, he plays it himself.

05:30.872 --> 05:32.999
He must be something to see.

05:33.083 --> 05:34.291
I'd love to go sometime.

05:34.376 --> 05:35.751
So go.

05:35.836 --> 05:37.253
Yes, I shouId.

05:37.337 --> 05:38.838
You will go with me.

05:38.922 --> 05:40.423
What?

05:40.507 --> 05:42.800
You would go with me?

05:42.884 --> 05:47.221
No. l don't want to impose
if you haνe plans.

05:47.347 --> 05:51.600
When you hear him, you will smile like this.

05:53.812 --> 05:55.104
Pick you up at 8.

05:55.188 --> 05:56.856
I live in Brooklyn. It's a hike.

05:56.940 --> 05:58.733
Neighbors.

06:00.360 --> 06:02.153
Joey says that Duck's in the blind.

06:02.237 --> 06:03.529
It's now or never.

06:24.760 --> 06:27.803
This is why l booked a day early.

06:27.888 --> 06:29.764
What did Ricardo in there say?

06:29.848 --> 06:31.974
He's in hourly contact with TWA,

06:32.059 --> 06:34.143
and they've offered
to buy you new luggage.

06:34.227 --> 06:35.978
And fill it with my things?

06:36.063 --> 06:39.440
Ricardo recommended a tailor. Chinese.

06:39.524 --> 06:43.277
And he said they've got
a whole shop full of swim trunks.

06:43.403 --> 06:45.237
I brought mine.

06:45.322 --> 06:47.573
There's not gonna be any swimming.

06:47.657 --> 06:50.576
The convention doesn't
start for another day.

06:50.660 --> 06:51.744
You want to be the hundredth person

06:51.828 --> 06:53.329
to shake someone's hand
at some convention?

06:53.413 --> 06:54.997
For what, a free pen?

06:55.082 --> 06:57.083
We'll follow up face to face.

06:57.167 --> 06:59.335
Forget Santa Monica.

06:59.419 --> 07:01.504
Take your list,
target some of these guys,

07:01.588 --> 07:03.297
and make them feel special.

07:03.423 --> 07:05.466
Didn't Roger give you leads?

07:05.550 --> 07:06.717
He did.

07:07.928 --> 07:09.512
I'm gonna need sunglasses.

07:14.059 --> 07:15.851
Come on.

07:15.936 --> 07:17.436
You want to be on vacation, Pete?

07:17.521 --> 07:19.146
Because I can make that happen.

08:09.823 --> 08:11.198
Old-fashioned.

08:14.578 --> 08:15.744
Excuse me.

08:17.080 --> 08:19.748
My friends and I have
been speculating about you,

08:19.833 --> 08:22.668
trying to decide who you are
and what you do.

08:22.752 --> 08:24.211
Why?

08:24.296 --> 08:26.088
Are you an actor?

08:26.173 --> 08:27.298
No.

08:27.382 --> 08:29.008
Are you an astronaut?

08:29.092 --> 08:30.176
No.

08:30.260 --> 08:32.219
Someone over there
would like to meet you--

08:32.304 --> 08:34.138
a young woman--

08:34.222 --> 08:36.807
only if you are none of these things.

08:41.188 --> 08:43.939
I'm Viscount Monteforte d'Alsace.

08:44.024 --> 08:45.774
- Willy.
- Don.

08:45.859 --> 08:48.152
This is Don.

08:48.236 --> 08:50.821
She's been staring at you all day.

08:50.906 --> 08:53.199
Can't stop talking about you.

08:54.367 --> 08:55.367
I'm Joy.

08:58.872 --> 09:01.582
And this is Rocci.

09:01.666 --> 09:05.836
You look so comfortable
alone by the pool all day.

09:05.921 --> 09:08.380
Made me wonder if you're
waiting for someone.

09:10.300 --> 09:11.967
I am.

09:13.094 --> 09:15.429
Do you smell that jasmine?

09:17.057 --> 09:18.265
Dine with us.

09:20.560 --> 09:21.810
Maybe another time.

09:21.895 --> 09:24.355
That never happens.

09:24.439 --> 09:25.773
Hello.

09:25.857 --> 09:28.234
Pete, this is Joy and Rocci

09:28.318 --> 09:30.277
and Viscount Monteforte.

09:30.362 --> 09:31.612
Very good.

09:31.696 --> 09:33.322
D'Alsace. Willy.

09:33.406 --> 09:35.032
That's quite a name.

09:35.116 --> 09:36.659
Peter Dykeman Campbell.

09:36.743 --> 09:38.744
Have we met somewhere? Newport?

09:38.828 --> 09:42.039
I have a terrible memory for faces.

09:42.123 --> 09:43.374
Nice meeting you.

09:43.458 --> 09:44.625
Yes.

09:44.709 --> 09:45.960
A pleasure to meet you.

09:49.839 --> 09:51.340
Look for us.

09:57.430 --> 10:00.557
Everybody here is late for everything.

10:00.642 --> 10:03.394
I just saw Tony Curtis in the men's room.

10:03.478 --> 10:05.562
Handing out towels?

10:05.647 --> 10:07.606
Tony Curtis, Don.

10:07.691 --> 10:09.358
A thing like that.

10:12.946 --> 10:14.530
Who's for dinner?

10:14.614 --> 10:15.698
Rodney Barnes.

10:15.782 --> 10:17.533
Classic salesman turned executive.

10:17.617 --> 10:20.911
And this interesting scientist,
Caleb Sawyer.

10:20.996 --> 10:23.414
He has this Optoman thesis.

10:23.498 --> 10:25.207
In addition to rockets,

10:25.292 --> 10:27.376
they're going to start engineering man--

10:27.460 --> 10:29.211
you know, for travel in space.

10:29.296 --> 10:32.589
New organs, super strength.

10:32.674 --> 10:34.633
You know the Soviets are working on it.

10:34.718 --> 10:37.011
Are all of our meetings like this?

10:37.095 --> 10:39.638
It's American Aviation and Rocketdyne.

10:39.723 --> 10:40.889
It's not a joke.

10:42.517 --> 10:44.518
Can I get a drink here or what?

10:55.196 --> 10:56.739
The Raphael was a little tired,

10:56.823 --> 11:00.242
but the Fifth Arrondissement
has most of your good restaurants.

11:00.327 --> 11:01.660
Of course, we kept getting lost,

11:01.745 --> 11:03.287
and every time Sherry asked for directions,

11:03.371 --> 11:05.414
it turned out to be another American.

11:05.498 --> 11:06.874
Well, there you go.

11:06.958 --> 11:10.252
I'll take Jane to Paris,
and I'll send Mona to Reno.

11:10.337 --> 11:11.754
You don't have to marry her, do you?

11:11.838 --> 11:13.505
No.

11:13.590 --> 11:17.217
Maybe you and Mona could work out
one of those modern arrangements.

11:17.302 --> 11:18.719
George, stop.

11:18.803 --> 11:22.348
It is possible that you'll get tired of her,
and then where will you be?

11:22.432 --> 11:24.224
Mona doesn't haνe a right to anything--

11:24.309 --> 11:26.226
not my company money,
not my family money.

11:26.311 --> 11:28.354
She's lucky I'm giving her anything.

11:28.438 --> 11:30.439
And you know what?
We've been miserable for years.

11:30.523 --> 11:32.107
I don't want to die with that woman.

11:32.192 --> 11:33.650
Calm down.

11:33.735 --> 11:36.570
I didn't know that.

11:36.696 --> 11:39.698
This is the life I was always meant to haνe.

11:41.201 --> 11:42.785
Congratulations.

11:44.579 --> 11:47.331
Mona has the marriage license,
and she wants to hurt you.

11:47.415 --> 11:50.125
If you want to be with this 20-year-old girl,
you're going to have to buy it from her.

11:50.210 --> 11:51.418
I have to warn you.

11:51.503 --> 11:55.089
Women in this situation
become extra irrational.

11:55.173 --> 11:56.632
Well, how badly
does she want to hurt me?

11:56.716 --> 11:58.342
I have a list of conditions

11:58.426 --> 12:01.345
and an alimony that could
support Rita Hayworth.

12:01.429 --> 12:03.847
Think of all the good things
in life and cut them in half.

12:03.932 --> 12:07.017
l want you to push as hard
as you can, but I want it done.

12:07.102 --> 12:09.353
Mr. Phillips is here.

12:09.437 --> 12:10.896
In a minute.

12:12.565 --> 12:13.941
I'll proceed.

12:14.025 --> 12:17.236
But I want you to think about it.

12:19.322 --> 12:21.281
Duck Phillips, this is George Rothman.

12:21.366 --> 12:23.450
Actually, we know each other.

12:24.577 --> 12:26.328
Roger.

12:26.413 --> 12:27.996
It's good to see you, Duck.

12:43.221 --> 12:44.596
Was he for you or against you?

12:44.681 --> 12:46.181
He's supposed to be the best.

12:46.266 --> 12:47.307
Him or Marvin Hughes.

12:47.392 --> 12:49.309
That's who Mona has.

12:49.394 --> 12:50.769
He's her cousin.

12:52.480 --> 12:54.773
How bad was it? Do I want to know?

12:54.858 --> 12:57.860
I don't think my circumstances
were the same as yours.

13:05.702 --> 13:06.743
What can I do for you?

13:06.828 --> 13:09.329
Actually, this might not be
the best time to talk about this.

13:09.414 --> 13:11.248
Can't you tell I'd welcome
a change in subject?

13:11.332 --> 13:13.167
Well, good, then.

13:14.627 --> 13:16.253
What the hell, right?

13:19.215 --> 13:22.009
Listen, we're coming up
on two years together here.

13:23.136 --> 13:24.428
Did you get me something?

13:28.391 --> 13:32.853
I think we're at a point in time
where I need to know what your plans are.

13:32.937 --> 13:35.606
A partnership. I think I'νe earned it.

13:37.650 --> 13:38.859
Right.

13:40.487 --> 13:43.947
I'll bring it up at the next meeting
of the partners.

13:44.032 --> 13:45.741
Thank you.

13:45.825 --> 13:48.785
Of course you might have to come in
and be an advocate for yourself.

13:48.870 --> 13:50.370
I'd be proud to present
my accomplishments.

13:50.455 --> 13:52.748
Good. Because I'm at a loss.

13:54.000 --> 13:55.709
What is that supposed to mean?

13:55.835 --> 13:58.670
You haven't exactly deliνered
on that 30% you promised.

14:00.507 --> 14:02.841
I think we've really performed
in a very dismal year.

14:02.926 --> 14:05.010
These things are cyclical. You know that.

14:08.515 --> 14:10.974
Is there some question
about my value to Sterling Cooper?

14:11.059 --> 14:12.226
Just think about the board.

14:12.310 --> 14:13.977
Bert Cooper hates everyone.

14:14.062 --> 14:15.562
And his sister--

14:15.647 --> 14:17.731
well, she does whatever he says.

14:17.857 --> 14:20.526
Don, he's only 12 1/2%,

14:20.610 --> 14:23.570
but l can't say he's
your biggest cheerleader.

14:23.655 --> 14:25.072
What are you saying?

14:25.156 --> 14:26.698
Everyone thinks you're a fine fellow.

14:26.783 --> 14:31.286
But if I were you,
I'd go out there and make rain.

14:34.958 --> 14:37.292
Thank you for being so candid.

14:41.798 --> 14:44.550
This year we have seen
an historic collaboration

14:44.634 --> 14:46.093
in American aerospace.

14:46.177 --> 14:48.470
Building on Lockheed's new Polaris A3,

14:48.555 --> 14:50.055
Bell Aerosystems,

14:50.139 --> 14:51.765
Aerojet General, and NASA

14:51.891 --> 14:54.059
have developed a restartable rocket engine.

14:54.143 --> 14:56.395
Can we get the lights, please?

14:59.482 --> 15:01.316
We at Space Technology Laboratories

15:01.401 --> 15:05.487
have set our minds
to the challenges of the future.

15:05.572 --> 15:09.741
In July, Khrushcheν said the Soviet Union
now has an anti-missile

15:09.826 --> 15:12.327
that can hit a fly in outer space.

15:12.412 --> 15:16.415
Space Technology Laboratories
is leading a coordinated effort

15:16.499 --> 15:18.417
to create an invulnerable warhead--

15:18.501 --> 15:20.836
multiple, independently targetable

15:20.920 --> 15:22.921
reentry vehicles-- M.I.R.V.s.

15:23.006 --> 15:25.591
And North American Aνiation's
vernier thruster

15:25.675 --> 15:28.302
allows the primary missile
to correct its trajectory

15:28.386 --> 15:32.598
before shooting off several warheads
hidden inside its nose cone.

15:32.682 --> 15:34.683
The M.I.R.V. can be launched

15:34.767 --> 15:37.185
from a submarine or land
into the stratosphere.

15:39.272 --> 15:42.065
Then it splits off
into 14 individual warheads.

15:42.150 --> 15:44.735
That's 14 different targets.

15:46.237 --> 15:47.863
14 different cities.

15:47.947 --> 15:50.198
14 individual warheads,

15:50.283 --> 15:52.701
each with ten times
the payload of Nagasaki.

15:53.786 --> 15:56.955
Even if Khrushchev hits 35%,

15:57.040 --> 15:59.291
that's 5 out of 14.

15:59.375 --> 16:04.171
Secondary strike capabilities
will be extremely limited

16:04.255 --> 16:08.592
due to the decrease
in infrastructure and population.

16:10.637 --> 16:12.429
Total annihilation.

16:18.144 --> 16:20.270
Do you realize that one
of these companies

16:20.355 --> 16:23.398
spends more annually on media
than three Lucky Strikes?

16:23.483 --> 16:25.442
It's a gold rush.

16:27.570 --> 16:29.571
Where are the valets?

16:29.656 --> 16:31.365
So much for cheap labor.

16:31.449 --> 16:33.367
Go see if General Dynamics beat us here.

16:33.451 --> 16:35.077
Drop these by the front desk.

16:35.161 --> 16:37.162
You don't want them under your arm.

17:00.186 --> 17:01.436
Hello.

17:01.521 --> 17:03.855
I think you're happy to see me.

17:07.694 --> 17:10.278
Well, take a good look.
I have to be on my way.

17:10.363 --> 17:11.613
Are you working?

17:11.698 --> 17:14.074
Yes.

17:14.158 --> 17:15.909
That's too bad.

17:16.035 --> 17:17.744
I'm going to Palm Springs.

17:17.829 --> 17:19.496
You should come with me.

17:20.957 --> 17:22.666
I don't know about that.

17:25.795 --> 17:28.463
Why would you deny yourself
something you want?

18:06.919 --> 18:08.879
You want to get your things?

18:10.089 --> 18:11.256
No.

18:20.850 --> 18:22.476
Well.

18:22.560 --> 18:23.935
Why don't we give it a few more minutes?

18:24.020 --> 18:28.356
Enjoy the scenery, order some drinks.

18:28.441 --> 18:30.942
I think Don needed to make a phone call.

18:44.040 --> 18:45.457
Hello?

18:46.584 --> 18:48.001
Just leave the bags there.

18:51.798 --> 18:52.881
Who lives here?

18:52.965 --> 18:56.301
Friends. They're in Sardinia.

18:56.385 --> 18:58.178
I'm supposed to be in Edward's room.

19:11.317 --> 19:13.693
That's Stephanie in the swimming pool.

19:15.363 --> 19:17.489
And Willy and Rocci you've met.

19:20.034 --> 19:22.536
And there's Greta and her friend Carlos.

19:22.620 --> 19:25.163
I'm surprised to see them
in the same place.

19:27.834 --> 19:29.167
Come with me.

19:34.841 --> 19:36.091
Hello, Greta.

19:36.175 --> 19:38.593
Hello, Joy, darling.

19:39.846 --> 19:41.096
Who's this?

19:41.180 --> 19:43.098
This is my friend Don.

19:43.182 --> 19:45.559
I'm Carlos Villa Declan.

19:48.187 --> 19:49.980
It's medicinal.

19:56.320 --> 19:58.071
Good-bye, Carlos.

20:04.453 --> 20:06.413
Come for a swim with me?

20:10.668 --> 20:12.544
You can go inside
and ask for some trunks,

20:12.628 --> 20:14.504
or you can go au naturel.

20:19.260 --> 20:22.470
I think I should go inside.

20:22.555 --> 20:25.223
You're white as a sheet.

20:26.976 --> 20:28.727
Don, are you okay?

20:51.959 --> 20:53.168
Where am l?

20:53.252 --> 20:55.587
You're with me, remember?

20:55.671 --> 20:58.632
You have heat exhaustion.

20:58.716 --> 21:00.592
What are you doing?

21:00.676 --> 21:02.093
It's fine. It's medicine.

21:02.178 --> 21:03.803
Klaus is a doctor.

21:05.264 --> 21:06.556
No, it's okay.

21:06.641 --> 21:08.308
I just need some water and some aspirin.

21:11.103 --> 21:12.145
Everybody out.

21:12.271 --> 21:14.522
I thought you were going
to break your neck.

21:14.607 --> 21:18.193
Next time you feel faint,
lean towards the pool.

21:18.277 --> 21:19.819
See you at dinner.

21:19.904 --> 21:22.656
Little girl, don't get any ideas.

21:22.740 --> 21:24.741
This man needs rest.

21:27.870 --> 21:29.996
I found you some clothes upstairs.

21:35.586 --> 21:37.712
Who are these people?

21:38.756 --> 21:40.006
They're friends.

21:43.928 --> 21:45.929
We're nomads together.

